<p><strong>Here&rsquo;s what the creators have said about future seasons</strong></p>

<p>Although HBO has not confirmed a renewal, Andy Muschietti has already shared plans beyond Season 1. Speaking to Variety in October, he said the story is designed to run much longer.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Our big story arc involves three seasons, mainly based on the three critical cycles of Pennywise, which are 1962, 1935 and 1908,&rdquo; Muschietti said.</p>

<p>He also explained that the series takes inspiration from Stephen King&rsquo;s novel in a unique way. While the IT films adapted the main storyline, the show looks deeper into the book&rsquo;s background sections.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Welcome to Derry explores the deeper lore alluded to throughout the book,&rdquo; Muschietti told Variety. &ldquo;I went into the book and looked at the interludes. I realized there was a hidden story there&hellip; It&rsquo;s a story told backwards.&rdquo;</p>

<p>With strong ratings, a clear multi-season plan, and <a href="https://www.pinkvilla.com/entertainment/hollywood/it-welcome-to-derry-trailer-brings-pennywise-back-to-haunt-kids-in-sinister-and-creepy-town-watch-1388609">Bill Skarsgard&rsquo;s Pennywise</a> still central to the story, IT: Welcome to Derry Season 2 looks likely, even if it is not official yet. For now, fans can watch the Season 1 finale Sunday night on HBO and HBO Max and wait for an announcement that could bring Pennywise back to Derry once again.</p>
